#Text=John Wingfield
#Text=For others , see John Wingfield ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Sir John Wingfield ( before 1582 – 1596 ) was an English soldier .
#Text=Life
#Text=He was the third son of Richard Wingfield of Wantisden in Suffolk , and Mary , daughter and coheiress of John Hardwick of Derby , and the sister of Bess of Hardwick .
#Text=His brother Anthony Wingfield was reader in Greek to Elizabeth I of England .
#Text=He was a Member of the Parliament of England for Lichfield in 1593 . [ 1 ]
#Text=A volunteer against the Spanish in Holland , he was appointed captain of foot in the expedition there of Robert Dudley , 1st Earl of Leicester in December 1585 .
#Text=Wounded action before Zutphen on 22 September 1586 , he was knighted by Leicester .
#Text=He was one of the twelve knights , friends and relations , who walked at the funeral of Sir Philip Sidney on 16 February 1587 .
#Text=Returning to the Netherlands , he was appointed governor of Geertruidenberg .

#Text=With the assistance furnished him by his brother-in-law , Peregrine Bertie , 13th Baron Willoughby de Eresby , he managed to hold out successfully during 1588 , and to assist materially in forcing Alexander Farnese , Duke of Parma to raise the siege of Bergen in November .
#Text=His position , though , suffered from tension between the English auxiliaries and the States-General .
#Text=The garrison lacked pay , and was mutinous .
#Text=A rumour arose that he intended to hand over the place to the Spanish , and Maurice of Nassau came with a demand for its surrender .
#Text=Wingfield denied the imputed treason ; but Geertruidenberg was on 10 April 1589 , delivered to the Spanish .

#Text=Returning to England with his wife and newly born child , Wingfield served as master of the ordnance under Sir John Norris in Brittany against the forces of the Catholic League in 1591 , and the following year he is mentioned as being in charge of the storehouse at Dieppe .
#Text=In June 1596 he sailed on board the Vanguard , as camp-master with the rank of colonel , in the expedition under Robert Devereux , 2nd Earl of Essex against Cadiz .
#Text=After an attack on the Spanish fleet led by Walter Ralegh , in which he took part , he was one of the first to enter the town .
#Text=Ordered on 21 June to bait an ambush , Wingfield led 200 men along the isthmus leading to the city gates which were defended by 500 Spanish cavalry .
#Text=He then feigned a panic-stricken retreat and drew the Spanish back into the arms of a larger hidden English force .
#Text=In the rout that followed the English broke through the city gates and Wingfield was wounded in the thigh , while Essex and a small band fought through to the plaza .
#Text=Unable to walk , Wingfield captured a horse to follow Essex , and — now an obvious target — was killed instantly by a bullet to the head just as the city surrendered .
#Text=He was buried five days later with all the funerall solemnities of warre in the cathedral at Cadiz , while the generalls threw their handkerchiefs wet from their eyes into the grave ( Stow ) .
#Text=John Donne , a member of the expedition , composed the well-known epigram ( Farther then Wingefield , no man dares to go ) in tribute . [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=In the following year the queen granted his widow an annuity of £100 a year .
#Text=Family

#Text=Wingfield married , about 1582 , Susan Bertie , countess of Kent , sister of Peregrine Bertie , Lord Willoughby de Eresby , and widow of Reginald Grey , 5th Earl of Kent , by whom he had two sons , Peregrine , born in Holland , presumably named after her brother , and Robert Wingfield .
